# PodPilot Architecture

## Stack
- **Backend:** .NET 10, Clean Architecture, CQRS (MediatR), FluentValidation, EF Core + MySQL
- **Frontend:** React 19, TypeScript, Vite, React Query, reactstrap, react-hook-form
- **Auth:** JWT + org-scoped RBAC (`organization_id`, `organization_role` claims)

## Layer boundaries (strict)
| Layer | May depend on | Must NOT depend on |
|-------|---------------|-------------------|
| Domain | Nothing | Application, Infrastructure, Api, Contracts |
| Application | Domain, Contracts | Infrastructure, Api, provider SDKs |
| Infrastructure | Application, Domain | Api |
| Api | Application, Contracts | Infrastructure types directly |
| Contracts | Nothing framework-specific | Application handlers |

## Provider abstractions
- `IComputeProvider` / `IPodProvider` live in **Application** interfaces only
- RunPod and future providers implement in **Infrastructure** only
- Handlers call `IProviderService` / `IPodService` — never `RunPodProvider` or HTTP clients

## Scalability rules
- Organization-scope every tenant resource via JWT `organization_id`; enforce in handlers, not controllers
- Use CQRS: thin controllers → MediatR commands/queries → validators → handlers
- Keep handlers idempotent where possible; use single `SaveChangesAsync` per logical transaction when feasible
- Add new providers by implementing interfaces + factory registration — do not modify existing business handlers

## Security
- Encrypt API keys at rest; never return secrets in API responses
- Enforce permissions via `IOrganizationAuthorizationService` in handlers
- Log audit events for create/update/delete mutations

## Quality bar
- `TreatWarningsAsErrors` is on — code must compile with zero warnings
- No TODOs, placeholders, or stub implementations in committed code
- All public APIs async; no blocking calls in request paths
